# A03 — Bridging Neuroscience and Artificial Intelligence

**Course:** ITAI 4374 — Neuroscience as a Model for AI Systems
**Instructor:** Professor Patricia McManus
**Student:** Muhammad Umer | Houston City College | Spring 2026

## Problem

This assignment examined specific pathways through which neuroscience research has influenced AI system design and proposed directions for deeper integration going forward.

## Approach and Methods

I selected three case studies where neuroscience directly shaped AI architecture:

1. Attention mechanisms — derived from research on selective attention in the primate visual system
2. Dropout regularization — linked to stochastic firing patterns of biological neurons
3. Predictive coding — a neuroscience theory being explored as an alternative to backpropagation

## Results and Interpretation

The most productive transfers from neuroscience to AI occur when a specific computational problem maps cleanly onto a known biological solution. Attention mechanisms succeeded because the problem of selectively weighting inputs is well-defined in both domains. Neuroscience is most valuable to AI not as a blueprint to copy but as a source of principles to adapt.
